node.text: I recently had the opportunity to direct the launch film for @gcsports by @dickssportinggoods.  Was such a great time getting to revisit team sports and to see the absolute passion and dedication these players have.  Big thanks to all of our coaches and athletes, I wish you all tons of success.  Thank you to our incredible team @kentvtcru @ana.de.diego @treefiddy5 @sstieg @teddymuse @tonightshigh_score @kevin_denning @nathanieldueber @fullmetaljackie747 @cyrus_reynolds @danorst @jeffpaceaudio @mpolanski80 @axis.innovations @shotoversystems @sonyalpha and everyone else who made this a reality 🙏🏼❤️ (shot on Sony Venice / Cooke FF anamorphics)

node.text:
I recently had the opportunity to partner up with @joseph.nikolai to direct the new ProV1 launch for @titleist.  The goal was simple; experience a golf ball in a way we haven’t yet seen.  Turning the dream into a reality however was immensely challenging but ultimately worked out.  Huge thanks to @johnny_fpv for stepping up to the plate and helping realize the vision.  Thank you to my brother @mbeauchesne1 for everything you brought to the table on this one.  Big thanks to the entire Titleist staff and team for having me. Thanks to my amazing producer @ana.de.diego and our team @mussoinc @davidgwilsondp @teddymuse @tonightshigh_score @akirschhoffer @markpettograsso 
@kevin_denning @cyrus_reynolds @hamiltonick @motionstate @danorst @robsbessette and everyone else involved.  Much love to my partners @shotoversystems @sonyalpha @legendtrailers and to all the film makers and photographers out there that go full send.  Cheers

Thankful for the opportunity to direct this new launch campaign for @sonyalpha.  I can remember pacing around my yard trying to think of the best scenes for this one and couldn’t seem to shake the idea of a live orchestra playing on a rooftop downtown as the backbone of the piece.  The problem was, we had to start shooting in just over a week and I didn’t have a score to work with so, I called @cyrusreynolds with a “small” request. He quickly wrote the score while on the road, sent to a team in Budapest to record live, then sent to our players in LA to practice and days later I was on an elevator heading up to the roof of a high-rise downtown to meet the orchestra for our first shoot of the film.  Many fairly complex shoots around the country later, we were sitting on 50+ hours of 8k goodness and at this point, version 100 of our score. The computers were about to get their meal.  Very little sleep, a lot of trial and error (per the usual) but after a month locked in the cave, climbing pixel mountain, we arrived at what you see here.  I hope you enjoy and I hope you can use this powerful new tool to go tell some world changing stories, we need them.  As you can imagine, this one took an army. Thankful for all of your involvement in this project and to Sony for your relentless pursuit of progression, this camera is one giant leap forward
.

node.text: Over 18,000 frames and over 200 gigs stacked through a process I have been exploring using a cinema camera mounted to a telescope.  Interference from the Earths turbulent atmosphere seen through this focal length (5600mm) makes a single exposure partially blurred and due to a very small aperture the images are quite noisy.  Stack thousands of frames and average them out and not only does the noise fade away but the sharp pixels remain and the blurred get trashed. This is just my first test and its not perfect but pretty wild to see the possibilities here.  I’m hoping over the next months to be able to create a multi terabyte image pulled from a massive mosaic of frames shot at 11200mm.  If anyone happens to have a 500 ft wide printer, please DM me.

node.text: It’s wild to think that both of the movies I spent the majority of my career making would end up going head to head for best snowboard film in history tomorrow on my birthday. I look back to the days my VHS player would overheat watching shred films on repeat. At 15 I got sponsored by Lib Tech and eventually went to Rossignol to join @travisrice and team.  Watching him ride was overwhelming, he took it to a place I didn’t know existed. Everything was going well until over the course of a season, I broke my back in multiple places, multiple times and eventually had to leave everything I worked towards and move on.  I was 18 at this point and had my first real crisis on my hands.  What do you do when everything you have worked towards evaporates? Everything you identify with goes out the window? Well in my case I picked up a camera and filmed the guys I used to ride with. It was as close as I could get to what I had loved. Making films would become my new obsession and eventually I found that same feeling I got got from snowboarding, in filmmaking.  Fast forward a hand full of practice movies, I had the opportunity to make ‘That’s it, That’s all’ with Travis and friends.  I had been feeling like his snowboarding was getting better then my filmmaking so I started to get competitive in a way.  I had an opportunity to use the first cineflex system that we mounted on a helicopter in New Zealand and I can remember tearing up my first day shooting with it.  I felt like I finally found a way to shoot on the level Travis and team were riding.  It was an absolute life changing moment for me.  Fast forward, ‘Art of Flight’ and so on... Now I sit here many years later after some big wins and shocking losses and I look back in thanks for everything I have been able to experience and learn along the way.  In a celebration of snowboarding and filmmaking I wanted to share some of those first life altering moments captured in NZ for ‘That’s it, That’s all’. A huge thank you to my Family, friends, team mates and brands that have helped make this shared experience that is life, so great.  Please enjoy and follow your passion, even if it’s upstream.  Much Love.

node.text: Dreaming up the concepts for DARK MATTER was the easy part.  Turning the vision into reality however was quite the intensive task.  Thankfully @danorst was willing to join our team and help us through the process.  Hundreds of hours of exploration and experimenting later, we finally got to see the initial idea become reality.  Here is a little look under the hood of how we made it all happen including tracking all of the media, taking daytime drone shots and making them night, “Ghosting” our riders, rearranging mountain ranges, adding stars, atmosphere, Milky Way, moon, clouds etc.  Big thanks to everyone involved in this passion project and of course to my longtime friend and partner @travisrice for the opportunity to collaborate once again.  If you missed it the other day, the film is now free on amazon prime.

node.text: When we look up into the darkness of night we see just that, “darkness”. We refer to it as that because our eyes are incapable of absorbing what truly surrounds us, a sea of elements that make up our human bodies, illuminated by trillions of colorful suns. An incomprehensible vastness, paintings on the grandest of scales, bright as can be.  Here is a wide field photograph of the Iris Nebula and surrounding complex of dust and debris.  You can see some of the dust clouds are so thick that they block all of the light from the stars behind them.  I captured this on a calm dark night in Joshua tree Friday night in just a few hours of total exposure.  Nice to get back into some deep sky time.  Hope everyone is doing well.  Cheers /// tech: shot in LRGB / 40 Lum @ 200sec / 12RGB @ 200 sec respectively.  Pix / PS workflow.

node.text: At first I thought about shooting this mornings super flower blood moon (yeah) from somewhere near LA, keep things easy ya know.  Naturally, that plan got more complex so we decided to head out to the desert.  We arrived in Joshua tree Monday night stoked to get ready for the big day to come.  The following morning we woke to a nauseating weather report.  It looked like most of SoCal would be under a surprise blanket of cloud.  After combing maps and some fairly inconclusive weather reports, we rallied 6 hours north to the foothills of Yosemite.  Set up for 8 hours, slept for 2-3 with fingers crossed.  As you can see, we got it.  It felt good to have such an effort pay off.  But the payment really comes from the missions themselves, not necessarily just injecting another pic into the sea of data, it’s the the friends, the fires, the reroutes, the bug bites, the old man telling us about his fear of snails.  True story.  Anyhoo, hope everyone is great.  More soon compadres.  #lunareclipse #flowermoon #bloodmoon #supermoon

node.text: Great times out playing with cameras and exploring some new possibilities.  Excited to finally integrate the Flex 4k into the @shotoversystems F1.  So much potential in that combination.  Thanks to @artcordova.o  for throwing down, the future is looking bright for you bud.  Thank you to @kevin_denning for nailing the integration and to @shotoversystems @abelcine and @treefiddy5 for your support in making it happen.  Always a good time.  Hope everyone is doing well and staying creative 🙏🏼❤️

A night out with the Worm Moon. Although it’s quite obviously the same moon, this months moon is named so as it was historically used to signal that start of spring, when robins would come to town and harvest all the fresh wormy bois.  The reddish-orange appearance in the first videos and image is due to quite a bit of pollution and atmospheric dust in the observation path (that’s all the fun stuff we get to breathe). The following are higher in the sky where pollution and atmospheric distortion become less of a factor, luminance increases and the details start to pop.  #wormmoon #fullmoon #alpha1🪱

node.text: 64.6% waxing moon from last night testing out the A1 (no tracking, just tripod w/600x2 running TL). This is 100 frames stacked and averaged to increase detail lost from trashy LA atmospheric turbulence and you get the added bonus of a noise free image.  The color this camera produces is beautiful IMO.  Really helped in bringing out all of the mineral colors on the Moon.  I’m looking forward to more with this rig.  #alpha1

node.text: Manufactured mountains and our resident star unite for just a moment.  Four evenings over the past few weeks I have driven 40 miles from DTLA to try to make the connection between our giant gas ball sitting 92 million miles in the distance, with my favorite urban skyline.  Last night was one of the better of those line ups.  To me there is nothing Earth-shatteringly impressive about these shots in themselves but the process involved in getting them is truly rewarding. Love the mapping, planning and the dynamics of the hunt, the friends you get to spend time with discussing this wild existence (In this case @danorst) and all of the random roads, jacket ripping trails and snake laden hillsides that you wouldn’t otherwise experience.  Photography for me is a therapy unlike any other and I’m very much thankful for it.  Hope everyone is well and is out there soaking up some magic for the memory bank.

node.text: Ancient behemoths light up the surrounding darkness in Monoceros.  A luminous stellar nursery called the Cone and the Foxfur sit 2700 Light Years from us.  The birth of new stars creates turbulent winds and intense ultraviolet radiation that we can observe here from Earth. Mountains of cold molecular hydrogen gas and dust ripple their way through trillions of miles of this distant region in the Orion arm of our galaxy. This image is so large that if you were to place our entire solar system inside it at an equal distance, it wouldn’t register a pixel.  And although 2700 light years  sounds far, that is only 1/40th of the way across our galaxy, which is just one of hundreds of billions in our observable universe.  We are a flicker of light in an ocean of violent beauty, a single drop in it’s magnificent story.  #astrophotography #conenebula #foxfurnebula #spaceismetal
